<div id="pf5d" class="pf w4 h0" data-page-no="5d"><div class="pc pc5d w4 h0"><img class="bi x0 y0 w5 h1" alt="" src="bg5d.png"/><div class="t m6bc xe h1e y444 ff5 fs14 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">TUESDAY </div><div class="t m6bd x1b h40 y219 ff2 fs14 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">March 9 </div><div class="t m6be x1 h28 y656 ff5 fs18 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Seeds of the Spirit </div><div class="t m19 xb5 h3 y656 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">(John 1:32, 33; 3:5-8; 4:23, 24; </div><div class="t m160 x1 h3 y3e3 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">6:63; 7:37-39). </div><div class="t m540 x5c h3 y38 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">There are eleven passages in the Gospel of John that refer either </div><div class="t m453 x1 h3 y84b ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">directly or indirectly to the nature and work of the Holy Spirit. Five of </div><div class="t m376 x1 h3 y84c ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">these passages are located in the narrative section of the first half of </div><div class="t m250 x1 h3 y84d ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">the book. These passages mention the Spirit only in passing. It is as </div><div class="t m3ea x1 h3 y3a ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">though John were using these passages to plant seeds in the reader&apos;s </div><div class="t m341 x1 h3 y84e ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">mind that would sprout only in the fertile soil of Jesus&apos; farewell </div><div class="t m5f1 x1 h3 y3b ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">speech </div><div class="t m16b x14 h3 y3b ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">(John 13-16). </div><div class="t m1d9 x8f h3b y84f ff5 fs21 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">What </div><div class="t m113 x5c h9 y3c ff5 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> can we learn about the </div><div class="t m3e2 x13 h3 y357 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">work of the Spirit from John 1:32, 33; </div><div class="t m459 x1 h9 y850 ff5 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">3:5-8; 4:23, 24; and 7:37-39? </div><div class="t m371 x5c h3 y204 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Although the Spirit makes several appearances in the first half of </div><div class="t m365 x1 h3 y2e8 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">this Gospel, there is little information about Him. The Spirit makes it </div><div class="t m683 xbe h3 y2e9 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">possible for the Baptist to identify Jesus at the Jordan </div><div class="t m3bf xd7 h3 y77d ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">(John 1:32, 33). </div><div class="t m17c xbe h3 y2ea ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">He is an essential part of human participation in the kingdom of God </div><div class="t m2a1 xbe h3 y3e9 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">(John 3:5, 6). </div><div class="t m6bf x53 h3 y3e9 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Although His work cannot be controlled by human </div><div class="t m206 xbe h3 y851 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">beings, His effect on people can be seen </div><div class="t m6c0 xc2 h3 y3ea ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">(vs. 8). </div><div class="t m1b7 xc h3 y3ea ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Worship is no longer </div><div class="t m27d xbe h3 y2ec ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">tied down to specific locations or temples, nor is it limited to any par-</div><div class="t m305 xbe h3 y662 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">ticular people </div><div class="t m18f x7e h3 y2ed ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">(John 4:23, 24). </div><div class="t m4db x98 h3 y2ed ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">He is available in every place and to </div><div class="t m151 xbe h3 y3eb ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">anyone of any background through the words of Jesus </div><div class="t m234 x32 h3 y4bc ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">(John 6:63). </div><div class="t m26a x6b h3 y20b ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">The exact nature of the Spirit&apos;s work would become manifest only </div><div class="t m36a xbe h3 y7c8 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">in the context of the Cross </div><div class="t m59 x8c h3 y3ed ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">(John 7:39). </div><div class="t m17f xc2 h3 y77e ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">So, John 7:37-39 is a transi-</div><div class="t m65b xbe h3 y3ee ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">tional passage, preparing the reader for the clearer, more-detailed </div><div class="t m506 x68 h3 y3ef ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">information about the Spirit&apos;s work that comes in the farewell dis-</div><div class="t m367 xbe h3 y3f0 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">course of John 13-16. John 20:22 (&quot;And . . . he breathed on them and </div><div class="t m276 xbe h3 y7ca ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">said, &apos;Receive the Holy Spirit&apos; &quot; </div><div class="t m604 xbc h3 y7ca ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">[NIVJ) </div><div class="t m202 x9 h3 y3f1 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">shows that the promise of </div><div class="t m5e6 x68 h3 y3f2 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">John 7:39 in fact began to be fulfilled right after Jesus&apos; &quot;glorifi-</div><div class="t m377 x68 h3 y55 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">cation&quot; on the cross. </div><div class="t m4bd x6b h3 y6bf ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">In John 14-16, the title given to the Spirit is a Greek noun that can </div><div class="t m2ec x68 h3 y852 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">be translated as &quot;Comforter&quot; or &quot;Counselor.&quot; The root meaning of </div><div class="t m4c4 x68 h3 y3a0 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">paraclete is </div><div class="t m372 x64 h3 y532 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">a person who is called alongside to help someone. So the </div><div class="t m610 x68 h3 y853 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">word can be used in the legal sense of a defense attorney at a trial who </div><div class="t m1b8 x68 h3 y854 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">appeals in behalf of another or as one who comes to comfort some-</div><div class="t m40c x68 h3 y855 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">one who is overwhelmed with grief at a time of loss. Both meanings </div><div class="t m642 x68 h3 y7 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">fit well into the context of John 14-16. </div><div class="t m6c1 x3e h3 y5e5 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">91 </div></div><div class="pi" data-data='{"ctm":[1.000000,0.000000,0.000000,1.000000,0.000000,0.000000]}'></div></div>
